											<td width="100%" valign="top">					
												<!-- START NEWS AREAS-->
												<table width="90%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
													<tr><td valign="top" width="100%">&nbsp;<br>
													<!-- strMainData goes here-->
													<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='header' bgcolor='black' width='100%'>PALADIN STRATEGIES AND PLAYGUIDES</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='spti'>BASIC PALADIN PVP FOR UPPER LEVELS</font> - <small>Aanien the Scaled Claw, Rallos Zek</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>Let me start off by stating that I have been playing on Rallos Zek for almost all of my EQ life.  From this serever, many players learn the tricks of the traid when it comes to PVP.  If you dont you die, simple as that.  With that said, I will now tell you the basic strategy that I use in PvP. <P> First of all, as a paladin, you will never be an effective PK.  Alone, you just dont have the ability to do enough damage in a short enough time to kill somone.  The biggest Key to pvp with the paladin is knowing your opponent.  If they are naked, then you know that with a few quick clicks of the egg shaped pummice, and they will be a sitting duck for your stuns, roots, and blinds.  Also, know the class of your opponent.  If they are a caster, then blinding them while there nuking you doesnt do much good, but rooting them and then cutting into them is a very effective stragity. <P>  Fighting a caster: Make sure that you know what class they are, and weather or not they have a pet.  If they do, your #1 goal is to keep the pet blind.  When the pet is blind, it runs off in a random direction and is no longer a thret untill the spell wears off, at which point you re-cast and bye bye pet.  Now your second goal is to keep the caster from actually casting spells on you.  This is were knowing your opponent comes in.  If they are naked and have been stripped of there buffs, feel free to use you stuns on them, it will in most cases inturupt the casting.  If they are an equiped opponent, be sure that you use your shield to bash, this is your only hope at stopping there big nukes.  If indeed they are equiped and your spells are allways being resisted, it is important to save your mana for heals then.  If this is done properly, it is very hard to kill a paladin that constantly heals the damage that is done to him. <P> Most casters will simply play tag with you, they will cast a spell, run around a bit, and then cast another untill they are oom, your dead or there dead.  My best advise is to do your best to follow them, in big open areas this can be very hard, but it is what you have to do.  From there, the strategy is simple.  Cut them down.  Chase that little gnome wizzard and relish the sound he makes when you cut him. <P> The next secton deals with paladin vs tank in pvp.  In this case, root will be basically useless because you have to melee them to kill them, and they have to melee you to kill you. So, rely on the fact that you have healing.  When you take the hit points of a paladin+his healing+lay hands, he has almost double the hitpoints of a warrior and any other melee class.  Use that to your advantage.  Also, if they are naked, then there magic resistance is low, and you can stick blinds on them, then do it.  Once there blind, run to there back and start killin'. <P>  Finnaly, your resistances are very important.  It is of the utmost importance that you have a high MR when fighing a player that casts spells.  They will not be able to kill you if they cant keep you from running a way.  <P> Countering spells: When "weekened" reckless strenght will remove this.  When "incapasitated" an ac buff such as guard will remve this (note that if you have an AC buff up, you have to cancel it before you re-cast)  If you are Tashanied then the spell cure poision will remove it.  Shaman De-buffs I believe can be removed with pumice.  <P> Good luck to all you paladin PvPers.  I hope my tips have been helpfull.</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>&nbsp;</td></tr>
